    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "acc29c33_abf1925d",
        "filename": "go/common/signal.go",
        "patchSetId": 8
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 5120
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-11-08T18:03:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "My thinking is:\n1. For cases where we just want to run something when the program exits, using the cleanup package seems like the best abstraction. I don\u0027t really care about signals at all, or how the cleanup package works.\n2. For other cases, I think it\u0027s better to use the golang signal package directly. (OTOH, if I want to trap SIGINT or SIGTERM and do something other than exit, I would need to disable the signal handlers in this file somehow.)",
      "parentUuid": "56eb3f94_715960fc",
      "revId": "327cf21ae30c426959c33492548c0e2da934a471",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "90331a51_572fb34e",
        "filename": "go/common/signal.go",
        "patchSetId": 8
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 5015
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-11-09T13:59:57Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Okay, I moved this to a new go/signal package.  Added ability to handle multiple signals.  The package has a single public function, OnInterrupt, which handles both SIGINT and SIGTERM and is only enabled if OnInterrupt is called.  I left the signalHandler implementation, which *might* be useful in the future if someone wanted to send SIGUSR messages between programs, though I\u0027d argue that HTTP handlers would be more natural given our typical flow.\n\nI have a slight concern having this outside of common.  I would really like there to be an understanding that there is a single, central place for handling these signals.  With this in a separate signal package it\u0027s opt-in, but it may be unexpected that some package somewhere deeply nested inside the program can opt the whole program in to this behavior.  Forcing all programs to be opted in via common at least makes it clearer.\n\nFor #1 I had only been thinking about the case where the program exits due to receiving a signal, as opposed to \"normally\".  I added a sync.Once to the cleanup package and a note to the cleanup.Cleanup() function indicating that if you want cleanup to occur when the program exits normally you should do `defer cleanup.Cleanup()` in main().  I think that supports this use case better.\n\nFor #2, IMO doing something other than exit for those two signals seems like bad behavior, but I dunno.",
      "parentUuid": "acc29c33_abf1925d",
      "revId": "327cf21ae30c426959c33492548c0e2da934a471",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
